      "content": "Certainly! When you pay an extra $100 a month on your student loan, that additional payment first goes towards the principal balance. This means you are reducing the amount of money on which interest is calculated for the next month. As a result, the interest for the following month will be lower because it's based on a smaller principal balance. Over time, this can significantly reduce the total amount of interest you pay and shorten the life of the loan. To calculate the exact savings, you would need to know the interest rate of your loan and use an amortization schedule, which shows how each payment is split between principal and interest over the life of the loan. By comparing the amortization schedule with and without the extra payments, you can see the difference in total interest paid and the time it takes to pay off the loan.",
